I would like to test if mpg has any influence on qsec. I believe cars with a lower mpg have larger engines and therefore have better quarter-mile times. Lets test this theory.

qsecmpg <- lm(mtcars$qsec ~ mtcars$mpg)
plot(mtcars$qsec,mtcars$mpg)
abline(qsecmpg)

This linear model seems to fit my theory. Lets use regression to see if we can strengthen the case.

summary(qsecmpg)

## F-statistic: 6.377 on 1 and 30 DF,  p-value: 0.01708

In this case, the y-intercept is a0 = 15.3548 and the slope is a1 = 0.1241. Thus, the final regression model is:

qsec = 15.3548 + 0.1241 * mpg

For a good model, we typically would like to see a standard error that is at least five to ten times smaller than the corresponding coefficient. For example, the standard error for mpg is 2.52 times smaller than the coefficient value (0.12414/0.04916 = 2.52). This small ratio means that there is high levels of variability in the slope estimate, a1. The standard error for the intercept, a0, is 1.02978, which is roughly the same as the estimated value of 15.35477 for this coefficient. These values suggest that the estimate of this coefficient for this model does not vary much.

The reported R2 of 0.1753 for this model means that the model only explains 17.53 percent of the datas variation.

plot(fitted(qsecmpg),resid(qsecmpg))

Overall, this plot tells us that using the mpg as the sole predictor in the regression model does not sufficiently or fully explain the data. There is no observable trend or pattern in the residuals.

qqnorm(resid(qsecmpg))
qqline(resid(qsecmpg))

The residuals seem to be normally distributed, the points plotted in this figure seem to follow the straight line well.
